2 Load data

The data has been prepared for analysis with four scripts in the same repository (https://github.com/angela34a/HBTC_micro/tree/main/Data%20cleaning).

The metadata has been cleaned of unnecessary variables, as well as combined together from both the spring and fall sampling campain. It has, furthermore, been decontaminated by the decontam package, the contaminants and blanks were then removed from the count table, replicates of the same sampling site were summed up, and, finally, the temperature categorization has been added as a variable.

The final count table and taxonomy table (no contaminat ASVs and no blank samples) and clean metadata info is loaded in this chunk.

3 Alpha diversity

The richness and diversity of the samples has been analysed by temperature (in linear form, and categorical), by geographic location and by aquifer type.

3.1 Temperature distribution

The temperature categorization was done in previous script and consists of <10, 10-12, 12-14, 14-16, 16-18, 18-20, 20< samples and the reference samples.

# calculate Shannon's index with vegan
shannondiv <- vegan::diversity(t(asv_table))
# turning Shannon to effective number of species 
# to be more comparable across studies 
ens <- exp(shannondiv)


# make figure to plot later
p1_en <- cbind(as.data.frame(ens), as.factor(metadata$category)) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>%
  rename("div"= "ens",
         "temp"="as.factor(metadata$category)") %>%
  filter(temp != "NA") %>% 
# plot
  ggplot( aes(x = temp, y = div, fill = temp)) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, size = 3, shape=21, aes(fill = temp) ) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha=0.5, outlier.shape = NA) +
# add custom palette  
  scale_fill_manual(values = pal3) +
# make  the figure more readable  
  theme(legend.position = "none",
        axis.title=element_text(size=14,face="bold"),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size=10,face="bold"),

  labs(x = "Temperature category",
       y = "Shannon diversity index",
       title = "Diversity by temp. category") +
  scale_x_discrete(limits = name_vector)

Testing if the distribution of alpha diversity per temperature categories is significant and can be added to the figure in a * form.

To perform ANOVA, the assumption of normality and homoscedasticity were checked.

# 1. assumption - normal distribution: 
# Each population to be compared should be normally distributed 

cbind( as.data.frame(ens), metadata$category) %>%
  rename("cat" = "metadata$category" ) %>% 
  filter(cat != "NA") %>% 
  group_by(cat) %>% 
  do(tidy(shapiro.test(.$ens))) %>% 
  dplyr::filter(p.value <0.06)
## # A tibble: 1  4
## # Groups:   cat [1]
##   cat   statistic p.value method                     
##   <chr>     <dbl>   <dbl> <chr>                      
## 1 20<       0.836  0.0527 Shapiro-Wilk normality test
# I would rather do a non-parametric test
# since >20 borders not normally distributed



# 2. assumption - homogeneity of variance: 
# Variance in the populations compared should be the same/similar. 
cbind( as.data.frame(ens), metadata$category) %>%
  rename("cat" = "metadata$category" ) %>% 
  filter(cat != "NA") %>% 
  levene_test(ens ~ cat) %>% 
  dplyr::select("p") 
## # A tibble: 1  1
##       p
##   <dbl>
## 1 0.952
# assumption met
# but irrelevant
# do non-parametric anova
cbind( as.data.frame(ens), metadata$category) %>%
  rename("cat" = "metadata$category" ) %>% 
  filter(cat != "NA") %>% 
  kruskal_test(ens ~ cat)
## # A tibble: 1  6
##   .y.       n statistic    df      p method        
## * <chr> <int>     <dbl> <int>  <dbl> <chr>         
## 1 ens     219      15.6     7 0.0294 Kruskal-Wallis
# significant difference between groups


# do post-hoc to see which
cbind( as.data.frame(ens), metadata$category) %>%
  rename("cat" = "metadata$category" ) %>% 
  filter(cat != "NA") %>% 
  dunn_test(ens ~ cat) %>% 
  dplyr::filter(p.adj < 0.05)
## # A tibble: 0  9
## #  9 variables: .y. <chr>, group1 <chr>, group2 <chr>, n1 <int>, n2 <int>, statistic <dbl>, p <dbl>, p.adj <dbl>, p.adj.signif <chr>
# post-hoc does not show individual difference
# so no adding to the plot

Since there is no clear significant difference shown by group, we will try to see if there is a linear trend.

3.2 Spatial distribution

Plot the diversity index on an interactive map to see if there is a geographical pattern to the alpha diversity.

# add mapview to change X and Y to standard crs
new_metadata2 <- metadata %>% 
  cbind(., as.data.frame(ens)) %>% 
  filter(Temp != "NA") %>% 
# add small value to coordinates for one of the campaigns
# so they do not overlap completely on the map  
  mutate(X = ifelse(grepl("fall", sample_season) , X + 45, X)) %>% 
  dplyr::select("ens", "X", "Y") %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  mutate( ens_cat = cut(ens, b=6) )  


pal <-  mapviewPalette("mapviewSpectralColors")

sf_data <- st_as_sf(new_metadata2, coords = c("X", "Y"),  crs = 31253)
mapview(sf_data,  map.types = "Stamen.Terrain", col.regions = pal(10),
        zcol= "ens_cat", zoom = 12, color="black", 
        cex = 5, alpha = 0.7 )

Does not seem to be the case, since even the reference samples are not uniform in the color palette. The pattern also changes seasonally. There is no uniformity in higher diversity locations, neither the city center nor the outskirts are predominately diverse/low in diversity.

3.3 Aquifer distributuion

We chose all the aquifers that had more than 5 sampling points to see whether there is an impact of aquifer categorisation on the diversity index.

cbind( metadata, ens ) %>% 
# filter out aquifers that have less than 5 sample points 
  dplyr::filter(! Geol_beb %in%  c("n.b.", "lokaler Aquifer",
                                   "Wiental", "Zubringer", "OF")) %>% 
# do not differentiate between the different Donauschotter samples 
                mutate(Geol_beb = case_when( 
                            grepl('DS', Geol_beb) ~ "Donauschotter", 
                                              TRUE ~ Geol_beb)) %>% 
  dplyr::select("ens", "Geol_beb", "Temp") %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
# plot
  ggplot(aes(x=Temp, y=ens)) + 
  geom_point(shape=21, size = 3, fill = "violet", alpha = 0.9, stroke = 0.5) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se= FALSE, color = "black") +
  facet_wrap(~ Geol_beb, scales = "free_y", ncol = 2) + 
  stat_poly_eq(use_label(c("eq", "adj.R2", "p")), 
               label.y = "bottom", small.p = TRUE,
               size = 3) + 
  labs(x = "Temperature [C]",
       y = "Sshannon's diversity index") +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_text(hjust = 0), 
        legend.position = "none",
        axis.title=element_text(size=14,face="bold"),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size=10,face="bold"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90),
        strip.text = element_text(size = 12))

All three aquifer types have a different range of temperature. Donauschotter with the most sampling points and the widest area, spans across the 5-20 C, while Liesingbach falls in the medium temperature range, and Schichtwasser on the warmer side of the spectrum.

While Schichtwasser groundwater exhibits the clearest trend, increasing (p<0.05), with a linear regression explaining 40% of the variation, it is unclear whether model is sensical from the biology point of view - it is questionable whether Schichtwasser can be regarded as an uniform aquifer categorization considering that individual ground wells within this category are wildly heterogenous.

3.4 Modelling

Considering that there is no clear impact of temperature, aquifer nor location on the diversity distribution, we look into what environmental variables significantly impact alpha diversity:

df_alpha <- metadata %>%  
  cbind(as.data.frame(ens)) %>% 
  dplyr::select(where(is.numeric)) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-c("NH4", # many NAs
            "X", "Y")) %>% # coordinates
  na.omit() %>% 
  scale(center = T, scale = T) %>% 
  as.data.frame()
 

# remove the highly correlated ones
cor_matrix <- cor(df_alpha)
highly_correlated <- caret::findCorrelation(cor_matrix, cutoff = 0.9)
df_alpha <- df_alpha[, -highly_correlated] 

# run individual regressions for each variable
varlist <- names(df_alpha)[-19]
models <- lapply(varlist, function(x) {
    form <- formula(paste("ens ~", x))
    lm(form, data=df_alpha)
})
# tidy up the results
lapply(models, function(x) tidy(x)) %>% bind_rows() -> ind_models
ind_models %>% filter(term != "(Intercept)") %>% filter(p.value<0.05)
## # A tibble: 0  5
## #  5 variables: term <chr>, estimate <dbl>, std.error <dbl>, statistic <dbl>, p.value <dbl>
# none are sign

No variables have a significant individual effect on the Shannons diversity index.

Lets see if there is a better fit of multiple regression of numeric variables:

fullModel = lm(ens ~ ., data=df_alpha) # model with all  variables

# remove high vif variables
car::vif(fullModel)  %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
  dplyr::rename("vif"=".") %>% 
  filter(vif<10)  %>% 
  rownames_to_column("envs") %>% 
  dplyr::select("envs")  -> colnames

df_alpha2 <- df_alpha %>% dplyr::select("ens", 
                                       which(colnames(df_alpha) %in% colnames$envs ))

fullModel = lm(ens ~ .  , data = df_alpha2) # model with all  variables


#choose
step.model<- MASS::stepAIC(fullModel, # start with a model containing no variables
                    direction = 'both', # run forward selection
                    trace = 0) # dont show step-by-step process of model selection

#summary(step.model) # none
RsquareAdj(step.model) # <2%
## $r.squared
## [1] 0.01924285
## 
## $adj.r.squared
## [1] 0.008973141

There is still no significant effect, even a combined one. Next step would be to go beyond the analysis by numeric and categorical variables (aquifer categorization), respectively, and try to go for an interplay of both categorical and numeric variables. To be done later.

4 Composition

The taxonomic composition by temeprature categories was done in form of barplot and bubble plot, and defined numerically.

No immediate difference can be seen. Nanoarchaea visibly the most abundant clalss in each category.

4.1 Bar plot

# detach(package:plyr, unload = TRUE)
# tried fixing conflicts from select and filter by detaching
# but it is a conflict with some other package as well
# simply continue adding dplyr:: before the command 

asv_table %>% 
  mutate_if(is.integer, as.numeric) %>% 
  mutate(class = tax_table$Class) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = -class, values_to = "abundance", names_to = "sample") %>%
  left_join(.,metadata, by = c("sample" = "sample_season")) %>%  
  dplyr::select ("abundance", "class", "category") %>%
# to remove those with no category
  dplyr::filter(category != "NA") %>% 
# to make NA classes Unclassified   
  replace_na(list(class ='Unclassified' )) %>%
  mutate(category = as.factor(category),
         class = as.factor(class)) %>%  
# to find relative abundance within each category  
  dplyr::group_by(category) %>%
  mutate (rel_abund = abundance / sum(abundance)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
# to sum up all the counts of one class from all the samples  
  dplyr::group_by(category, class) %>%
  summarise(rel_abund = sum(rel_abund)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
# those very rare categorize as Diverse others 
  dplyr::group_by(category, class) %>%
  mutate(class = case_when(rel_abund< 0.015~ "Diverse others", 
                           TRUE ~ class)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
# final regrouping after categorizing for Diverse others  
  dplyr::group_by(category, class) %>%
  summarise(rel_abund = sum(rel_abund)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%

# plot
  ggplot(aes(x = category, y = rel_abund, fill = class)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", color = "black") +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c25) +
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank(), legend.position="right",
        legend.text = element_text(size = 6),      # Adjust the text size
        legend.title = element_text(size = 6),
        legend.key.size = unit(0.4, "cm"),
        axis.title=element_text(size=14,face="bold"),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size=10,face="bold"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, face = "bold")) + 
  labs(x = "Temperature categories",
       y = "Relative abundance", 
       fill = "Class") +
  guides(fill=guide_legend(ncol = 1)) +
  scale_x_discrete(limits = name_vector)

5 Temperature-related abundance trends

After looking at alpha diversity for the temperature categories, and compositional differences per temperature categories at class level, here there is more mining for trends at lower taxonomic levels.

Since there is a lot of unclassified ASVs on lower taxonomic levels, order was esteemed low enough without losing too much information.

5.1 Linear

Searching for the significant linear trend between abundances and temperature:

# 1. clean taxonomy
tax_table %>% rownames_to_column("asv") %>%   
dplyr::select("asv", "Order") %>% 
# rename the unclassified taxa
replace_na(list(Order ='Unclassified' )) -> tax_order


# 2. manipulate data
asv_table %>% 
  rownames_to_column("asv") %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = -asv, names_to = "samples", values_to = "abundances") %>%
  
# connect to the order information  
  left_join(., tax_order, by = "asv") %>% 
  dplyr::select("samples", "Order", "abundances") %>% 
  group_by(samples, Order) %>% 

# sum up the abundance within each order (diff sp/taxa)  
  summarise(abund = sum(abundances)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  
# remove the samples where abundance is 0
  dplyr::filter(abund != "0") %>% 
  
# connect the asv data to the metadata (temperature)
  left_join(., metadata[,c("sample_season", "Temp")], 
            by = c("samples" = "sample_season") ) %>% 
  
# remove the samples that do not have methane measures  
 dplyr::filter(Temp != "NA") %>% 

# filter only the orders which are present in 40+ samples  
  group_by(Order) %>% 
  mutate(n = n()) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  dplyr::filter(n>40)  -> data_for_temp
# this is now 157 orders  


# look at correlations btw order abundances and temperature   
data_for_temp %>% 
 group_by(Order) %>%

# choose only significant

Although there are certain significant correlations of order abundance and temperature, the results get less clear when the regression formula is used. This could be a result of non-parametric methods, like the correlation we used, being generally less affected by outliers.

The only order I would be comfortable claiming shows dependence would be the Candidatus Roizmanbacteria.

5.2 By category

We start with the 157 orders (selected orders that were found in 40+ samples), and their abundances and temperature measurements. Instead of using the otherwise present temperature categorization with 2 C steps, new categorization was done with 0-13-15-15+ temperatures, since ~50% of data points is within the 13-16 range. This way the cold and warm extreme is on either side of the 13-16 spectrum.

6 Beta diversity

The rate of dissimilarity by temperature categories and aquifer type checked at genus level, which was deemed low enough taxonomy level, while not losing many unclassified species.

6.1 Temperature distribution

An nmds ordination is done with abundances summed at the genus level, and distances calculated, with a hellinger-transformed data, to account for the compositionality of data.

# tax clean
tax_table %>% rownames_to_column("asv") -> tax_tab

# aggregate to genus level
asv_table %>% 
  rownames_to_column("asv") %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = -asv, names_to = "samples", 
               values_to = "abundances") %>% 
  left_join(., tax_tab, by = "asv") %>% 
  dplyr::select("samples", "Genus", "abundances") %>%

The first PC mostly consist of variations in conductivity and mineral ions, as well as pH, which is why the cold samples fall away from the extremely hot ones along the x-axis.

Conclusion: there is no distinct clustering by temperature in terms of microbial communities, but the higher the temperature the bigger the dissimilarity/turnover of the sample communities.

There is two different clusters in terms of environmental conditions: >10 C samples and 18+ samples are separated along the first PCA axis, which was mostly influenced by pH, and various ions/conductivity. The pH variation is much more pronounced in the cold samples, than warm ones.

It is possible that the low rate of environmental variation results in low dissimilarity (cold samples), and high variability results in high dissimilarity (warm samples). However, it is unexpected that such a stark difference in pH levels of the cold samples would not result in a high dissimilarity, since pH is known to be an important factor with microbial communities.

Worth noting is the high environmental homogeneity of the reference samples, which have, on the other hand, high turnover rates. A possible theory could be that biotic selection gains more importance in a stable environment, resulting with more stohastic final communties.

Since there is no clear relationships that confirm the importance of temperature for the composition, we continue with constrained ordination, and the search for envrionmental factors other than temperature that could be significant.

7.1 Constrained ordination

We use the CAP ordination as an distance-based alternative to the RDA (which uses bray, as opposed to RDAs euclidean). Hellinger transformation (square root of relative abundances) is used to account for compositionality of data.

# env clean
# df_alpha - already scaled and selected the important variables

# aggregate to genus
# asv_aggregated - already done for nmds
 
# asv clean
# because some samples get removed because of NAs 
asv_aggregated [, which  ( colnames(asv_aggregated) %in% rownames(df_alpha)) ] -> sp.dat

# transform hellinger (or clr sometimes)
decostand(sp.dat, method = "hellinger") -> sp.dat
#clr(sp.dat) -> sp.dat

# 1. first model
simpleRDA <- capscale(t(sp.dat) ~  ., data = df_alpha ,
                 distance = "bray",
                 scaling = "sites")
# take only that are vif<10
env_vars_low_vif <- vif.cca(simpleRDA) %>% 
                    as.data.frame() %>% 
                    dplyr::rename("env" = ".") %>% 
                    dplyr::filter(env < 10) 

# make new environmental data with only low vif variables
df_alpha[,which(colnames(df_alpha) %in%  rownames(env_vars_low_vif) )] -> env.dat


# 2. model without them
simpleRDA <- capscale(t(sp.dat) ~  ., 
                      data=  env.dat ,
                 distance = "bray",
                 scaling = "sites")


# test all variables and axes
# canonical axes
anova.model <- anova.cca(simpleRDA, by='axis', step=1000)  
# no axes sign

# the whole model
anova.model2 <- anova.cca(simpleRDA, step=1000) #is sign
RsquareAdj(simpleRDA)$adj.r.squared # and explains <1%
## [1] 0.002119407
# env parameters
anova.model3 <- anova(simpleRDA, step=1000, by = "term") 
# none sign

None of the environmental variables are significant for the composition.

9 Conclusion

Few things we can claim with certainty are:

  • there is some indication of decreasing Shannon diversity with increasing temperatures, although this is not supported by significance.

  • the Schichtwasser aquifer shows an increase in diversity with a temperature increase (p<0.05)

  • none of the measured variables are able to provide good fit for the diversity pattern

  • the taxonomic composition of all temperature categories does not vary greatly, and in each it is Nanoarchaea that is dominant

  • methane-processing microorganisms were not clearly correlated to the methane levels

  • there is indication that Candidatus Roizmanbacteria, Desulfobacterales, Microtrichales, and Legionallales exhibit dependence with temperature, which is somewhat supported by significance

  • there is no distinct clustering by temperature in terms of microbial communities, but the higher the temperature the bigger the dissimilarity/turnover of the sample communities

  • there is indication that diversity is more impacted by the waste water and heavy metals (possible pollution), than temperature
